          years), growth represents the majority of your total retirement
          balance.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. Employer Match</h4>
        <p>
          Many employer retirement accounts match your contributions up to a
          specific percentage of your annual salary. Always aim to contribute at
          least enough to capture the full match limit—this is essentially "free
          money" adding to your future wealth.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">3. The 4% Withdrawal Rule</h4>
        <p>
          The 4% rule is a standard guideline to project sustainable annual
          withdrawals in retirement without running out of funds. Your estimated
          monthly retirement income is calculated as: `(Retirement Balance *
          0.04) / 12`.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          4. Real vs. Nominal Purchasing Power
        </h4>
        <p>
          Due to inflation, a dollar today will buy more than a dollar in the
          future. We discount your future nominal balance by the expected
          inflation rate to show your projected balance in today's real
          purchasing power terms.
        </p>
